It’s very important to clean the hot sauce bottle thoroughly as you don’t want any spicy juice to get into the soil. Pop off the top (the top that allows the hot sauce to slowly leak from the bottle) and fill the bottle with hot soapy water. Rinse and allow to dry. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/c0/Create-an-Automatic-Plant-Watering-Device-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Create-an-Automatic-Plant-Watering-Device-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/c0/Create-an-Automatic-Plant-Watering-Device-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/v4-759px-Create-an-Automatic-Plant-Watering-Device-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Consider removing the bottle label so it doesn’t soak into the soil while the hot sauce bottle is doing its job. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/87/Create-an-Automatic-Plant-Watering-Device-Step-2Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Create-an-Automatic-Plant-Watering-Device-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/87/Create-an-Automatic-Plant-Watering-Device-Step-2Bullet2.jpg/v4-759px-Create-an-Automatic-Plant-Watering-Device-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
